                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2000-10-30</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I have gotten several copies of this book, I think these photographs are amazing and deserve an award.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Gold Medal for Leibovitz</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2000-06-08</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This collection of photography at first struck me as being quite gloomy and severe. However, after a closer study of each image I realized that Leibovitz expertly captures so much of the primal emotion of physical exertion. The images range from eerily erotic to firecely competitive-- while also maintaining the dignity of each individual athlete. I'm typically not a big fan of b&w photography but here it really works. The starkness of each image allows the humanness of each athlete to really come through while simultaneously allowing the terror, agony, and glory of the human body in competition to shine.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A depressing, copycat, and discourteous book</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>8</span>
                      /
                      <span>14</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>1998-10-29</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Leibovitz is rightly known for her creative, bright, and offbeat celebrity portraits. This book by contrast seems to be of a copied style from another well-known photographer. It is as if Leibovitz, tired or uncreative, decided to try to clone someone else's style and pass herself off as a b&w "artiste."<P>The pictures themselves are dark, somber, and far from showing any sort of triumphant spirit, portray the athleticism as a dismal exercise, and the athletes themselves as unattractive dullards. <P>There is also discourtesy to the reader and a tacit message that the athletes themselves are less important than the photographer: the photos are NOT accompanied by the athlete's name, sport, or anything else. The reader must go all the way to the back of the book where the publisher grudgingly provides ONLY the name and sport, in microscopic type.<P>If you like depressing books that speak of photographer's self-indulgence and disinterest in both the reader and the subject, this book will do nicely.</span>
                  
              
